#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/pivots.md savings=9%
M|Pivo|tx|A pivot is a structured course correction designed to tst a new fundamental hypothesis abt the pd, st, or engine of growth. It is not a random change, a rebrand, or giving up. A pivot preserves what has been learned while changing what has not worked. The ability to pivot is the essential difference btw startups that succeed and those that run out of runway pursuing a flawed plan.
M|1. Z|tx|What was a single feature of the pd becomes the entire pd.
M|1. Z|**Ex|** Flickr started as an online multiplayer game called Game Neverending. The photo-sharing feature within the game was more popular than the game itself. The team pivoted to make photo sharing the entire pd.
M|1. Z|**Wh|** an show us engage deeply w/ one feature but ignore the rest. cs interviews consistently highlight a single capability.
M|2. Z|tx|What was the entire pd becomes a single feature of a larger pd.
M|2. Z|**Ex|** A startup building a task timer for freelancers discovers that cs also need invoicing, time tracking, and client management. The timer becomes one feature in a broader freelancer management suite.
M|2. Z|**Wh|** The current pd solves the problem but is too narrow to sustain a business. cs consistently ask for adjacent functionality.
M|3. C|tx|The pd solves a real problem, but for a different cs than originally intended.
M|3. C|**Ex|** A B2C fitness app built for gym-goers discovers that corporate HR departments are the most enthusiastic buyers, using it for employee wellness programs.
M|3. C|**Wh|** Unexpected cs segments show higher engagement, willingness to pay, or faster adoption than the target segment.
M|4. C|tx|The target cs has a different problem than the one you set out to solve, but one you are well-positioned to address.
M|4. C|**Ex|** Potbelly Sandwich Shop started as an antique store. The owner noticed cs were more interested in the sandwiches he served than the antiques. He pivoted to a sandwich restaurant.
M|4. C|**Wh|** cs discovery reveals that the intended problem ranks lo on the cs's priority list, but a related problem ranks hi.
M|5. P|tx|Change from an application to a platform (or vice versa).
M|5. P|**Ex|** A startup building a single an tool realizes the real opportunity is providing the infrastructure for others to bd an tools. It pivots from application to platform.
M|5. P|**Wh|** Third parties are building on top of your pd, or you realize the infrastructure you built has broader applicability than the application layer.
M|6. B|tx|Switch btw hi margin/lo volume (B2B/enterprise) and lo margin/hi volume (B2C/consumer) md.
M|6. B|**Ex|** A consumer photo editing app w/ lo conversion pivots to a white-label B2B solution for e-commerce companies that need automated pd photo editing.
M|6. B|**Wh|** Unit economics do not work in the current md. The same technology can serve a fundamentally different business md.
M|7. V|tx|Change how the company makes money. The pd stays the same, but the rv md changes.
M|7. V|**Ex|** A SaaS tool charging monthly subscriptions discovers that cs wld prefer to pay per transaction. Or a free tool w/ ad discovers that cs wld gladly pay to remove ad and get premium features.
M|7. V|**Wh|** cs love the pd but resist the current pricing md. rv is stagnant despite strong engagement.
M|8. E|Chan|from viral to paid, from paid to sticky, or from sticky to viral.
M|8. E|**Ex|** A sl app trying to grow virally discovers its viral coefficient is 0.3 and plateauing. It pivots to a paid acquisition st w/ strong unit economics.
M|8. E|**Wh|** The current growth engine is not producing sufficient results despite op. A different engine shows more promise based on pd characteristics.
M|9. C|tx|Change the distribution channel through which you reach cs.
M|9. C|**Ex|** A direct-to-consumer br pivots to selling through established retail partners when cs acquisition costs prove unsustainable for direct sales.
M|9. C|**Wh|** Current channel is too expensive, too slow, or reaches the wrong cs. A different channel offers better economics or reach.
M|10. |tx|Achieve the same solution using a fundamentally different technology.
M|10. |**Ex|** A startup providing human-powered data labeling pivots to machine learning-based labeling when the technology becomes capable enough. Same cs, same problem, different technology.
M|10. |**Wh|** New technology enables dramatically better economics, perf, or scalability for the same solution.
M|Data|tx|\| Signal \| Strength \| What It Suggests \|
M|Data|tx|\|--------\|----------\|-----------------\|
M|Data|tx|\| Cohort metrics flat for 3+ cycles despite experiments \| Strong \| Current approach has a ceiling \|
M|Data|tx|\| cs interviews consistently reveal a different need \| Strong \| cs need or segment pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| One feature gets 80%+ of engagement \| Strong \| Zoom-in pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| Unit economics do not improve w/ scale \| Strong \| Business architecture or value capture pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| Viral coefficient plateaus below 0.5 \| Moderate \| Engine of growth pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| cs love pd but churn after trial \| Moderate \| Value capture or cs segment pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| Acquisition cost rising while conversion falls \| Moderate \| Channel or cs segment pivot \|
M|Data|tx|\| cr dominates your positioning \| Moderate \| cs need, segment, or technology pivot \|
M|The |tx|Hold a formal "pivot or persevere" meeting at a regular cadence (every 4-8 weeks for early-stage startups).
M|The |**Me|**
M|The |tx|1. **rv the data** (30 minutes)
M|The |it|Present cohort metrics from the last period
M|The |it|Show experiment results and learnings
M|The |it|Compare current metrics to targets set in the previous meeting
M|The |tx|2. **Hear from cs** (20 minutes)
M|The |it|Share direct quotes and stories from recent cs interactions
M|The |it|Present patterns from support tickets, interviews, and surveys
M|The |tx|3. **Assess honestly** (20 minutes)
M|The |it|Are we making progress toward pd-mk fit?
M|The |it|Are our experiments producing diminishing returns?
M|The |it|What have we learned that changes our original assumptions?
M|The |tx|4. **Decide** (20 minutes)
M|The |- Pe|continue current st, plan nx experiments
M|The |- Pi|choose the pivot tp, define the new hypothesis
M|The |- In|need more data before deciding (max 2 weeks)
M|Lead|Thes|
M|Lead|it|[ ] Founders feel a persistent sense of unease they cannot articulate
M|Lead|it|[ ] Team enthusiasm for the current approach is declining
M|Lead|it|[ ] cs conversations feel forced or produce surprising rp
M|Lead|it|[ ] The team is spending more time selling internally than building
M|Lead|it|[ ] Experiments are getting more complex but producing less in
M|Lead|it|[ ] The "just one more feature" argument keeps recurring
M|Lead|it|[ ] Early adopters have stopped advocating for the pd
M|Lead|it|[ ] cr w/ similar pd are not gaining traction either (mk problem)
M|Inst|**Be|** Burbn, a location-based check-in app w/ photo sharing, gaming elements, and sl features. Feature-rich but unfocused.
M|Inst|**Si|** us largely ignored check-ins and games but heavily used photo sharing and filters. an showed 80%+ of engagement was photo-related.
M|Inst|**Pi|** Stripped everything except photo sharing w/ filters. Renamed to Instagram.
M|Inst|**Af|** 25,000 signups on day one. Acquired by Facebook for $1 billion within 2 years.
M|Slac|**Be|** Tiny Speck, a company building Glitch, a multiplayer online game.
M|Slac|**Si|** The game struggled to retain players, but the internal communication tool the team built to coordinate game dv was remarkably effective.
M|Slac|**Pi|** Abandoned the game. Focused entirely on the internal communication tool.
M|Slac|**Af|** Fastest-growing enterprise software in history at the time. Acquired by Salesforce for $27.7 billion.
M|YouT|**Be|** vd dating site ("Tune In, Hook Up") where us posted vd profiles.
M|YouT|**Si|** Almost no one used the dating feature. People uploaded random videos instead, inc pets, comedy, and personal vlogs.
M|YouT|**Pi|** Pivoted from dating to general-purpose vd sharing.
M|YouT|**Af|** Acquired by Google for $1.65 billion, became the second-largest search engine in the world.
M|Grou|**Be|** The Point, a platform for collective action cg (petitions, boycotts, fundraising).
M|Grou|**Si|** The only cg that consistently succeeded were group buying deals.
M|Grou|**Pi|** Focused exclusively on group buying deals. Launched as a WordPress blog w/ PDF coupons.
M|Grou|**Af|** Reached $1 billion in rv faster than any company in history at the time.
M|Twit|**Be|** Odeo, a podcast platform that was disrupted when Apple added podcasting to iTunes.
M|Twit|**Si|** During a company hackathon, Jack Dorsey pitched a short messaging service. The team used it internally and became addicted.
M|Twit|**Pi|** Abandoned the podcast platform. Built the short messaging service as Twitter.
M|Twit|**Af|** IPO at $31 billion mk cap. Became a global communication platform.
